1. Upload Data

Used the version that is found in the repository. However, I opened it as a xls file and not a cvs file before I did anything to have a better look at the data.

For simplicitys sake, I am looking at which zipcodes had the most inspections overall.

3. Gathered Geocodes

Please download the zipcode package in R.

## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.4.4

4. Finalized Dataset

I wanted the specific neighborhood names for easier interpretation of the trends, so I got each zipcodes location. However, many locations were just labeled as Boston so I manually searched nearby landmarks to get a better sense of the area. I deleted one row because the zipcode list did not have any matching points. (UPDATE: Because I was able to get the map to work, I dont think the actual neighborhoods are important / might weaken our analysis because it adds an element of bias.)

5. Generate a Map of Boston

Please download the ggmap package in R. Note: The output will be a url. To access the map, copy and paste the url but replace the xxx at the end of the url with the access code listed below.

## Google Maps API Terms of Service: https://cloud.google.com/maps-platform/terms/.

7. Final Output

(a) Join map and shapefile dataframes by zipcode (b) Overlay the two maps together (c) Create heat map visualization (d) Add labels (NOTE: I wasnt able to align the two maps perfectly, but I think the final output still works for this project)
